> You can either ignore the warning, since Netty is auto-detecting availability, or you can disable it explicitly with -Dio.netty.noUnsafe=true (note, this property have have a different name in the shaded version).

@chrisvest my fear about ignoring the warning is that this method might be removed altogether in a future Java release, making it much more of a blocker than just a warning. Regarding, providing those additional flags, since those will need to be done by the end-application owners and not library maintainers (in this case grpc-java), it is not a nice developer experience. Perhaps, it would be better if the default was changed to not use unsafe - to make it compatible with the direction the Java platform is headed in. Or, at the very least, make this configurable by the library that uses netty instead of the end-application.
(I am not involved with the development of the grpc lib, I am just a user).
